docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:7:Offdex currently has the right direction: a CLI, an Expo mobile app, a Next.js WebUI, shared packages, pairing, relay, and bridge foundations. It now needs to become an Official-grade Codex client: built on Codex App Server only, Codex-faithful in design, real-time across surfaces, task-complete on mobile, and complete enough that a daily Codex user can rely on it.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:11:Complete Offdex as a Codex-faithful mobile and web client for a local Codex session. The Offdex CLI is the single setup path: it validates Codex readiness, starts Codex App Server, starts the Offdex bridge, prints pairing and WebUI/PWA links, reports status, and handles recovery. Offdex Mobile and Offdex WebUI connect through the bridge, use a shared Codex client layer, and implement every stable Codex App Server capability in the best platform-native form possible.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:13:The mobile product is not a generic chat app and not a companion-only supervisor. It is a Codex-native mobile workspace: a Thread drawer, an Active turn workspace, and Inspector sheets for dense tasks such as diffs, command output, approvals, plans, runtime settings, git actions, skills, apps, and thread details. The WebUI/PWA is separate from the frozen landing page and should provide the same core Codex client workflows where browser platform constraints allow.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:15:Offdex must preserve a real-time shared session across Codex desktop, Mobile, and WebUI. A session started anywhere should be visible everywhere with no meaningful delay, preserving thread identity and catching up after reconnect without duplicates. Remodex remains inspiration for mobile patterns and edge cases, but Codex desktop behavior and Codex App Server protocol are the source of truth.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:42:24. As a user, I want to start a new thread from the drawer, so that mobile creation is first-class.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:50:32. As a user, I want approvals adapted to mobile layout, so that I can approve or deny accurately with one hand.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:58:40. As a user, I want model, reasoning, sandbox, and approval controls where Codex supports them, so that mobile has the same power as desktop.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:62:44. As a user, I want image attachments from camera or library, so that mobile can provide visual context to Codex.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:70:52. As a user, I want branch and worktree actions to be careful, so that mobile git workflows do not damage local work.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:71:53. As a user, I want PR draft generation where supported, so that mobile can finish the coding loop.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:74:56. As an Android user, I want a native Android build, so that I get the best mobile experience.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:75:57. As an Android user, I want Play distribution and APK releases, so that installation is straightforward.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:99:- Offdex Mobile uses a Codex-native mobile workspace: Thread drawer, Active turn workspace, and Inspector sheets.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:103:- The visual design should be as close as possible to OpenAI Codex app and brand identity while using Offdex-owned implementation assets and mobile-native adaptations.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:104:- Expo APIs and React Native are the default for mobile. Software Mansion libraries should be used where they improve core UX or performance. Custom native modules should be used only where platform integration, performance, secure storage, background/reconnect behavior, deep links, or input gaps justify the cost.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:105:- Companion capabilities are allowed when they improve mobile Codex use without replacing Codex behavior. Current companion capabilities include git workflows, notifications, trusted reconnect, QR recovery, bridge diagnostics, and image attachment pipeline.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:111:- Android native distribution is first-class because Google Play Developer access exists; APK releases remain useful.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:112:- Unknown product or UX decisions follow the Codex-first decision rule: inspect Codex desktop first, Codex App Server protocol second, Remodex only as mobile inspiration or edge-case evidence, then document deliberate divergence before building it.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:125:- Distribution tests should cover Android build/release expectations, APK artifact expectations, PWA manifest/service worker behavior, and native iOS readiness without requiring App Store distribution.
docs/prd/offdex-completion.md:126:- Existing prior art includes nearby `bun test` suites in `packages/protocol`, `packages/bridge`, `packages/relay`, `packages/control-plane`, `packages/npm`, `apps/mobile/test`, and `apps/web/test`.
